<paragraph blockId="220.[454,1475,1546,1610]" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hong-Wa" authorityYear="2016" box="[454,706,1546,1572]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" genus="Noronhia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="220" pageNumber="220" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="randrianaivoi">
<emphasis box="[454,706,1546,1572]" italics="true" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">Noronhia randrianaivoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in mid-elevation transitional forests and basement rocks in Andohahela PN in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[771,903,1584,1610]" name="Madagascar" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[916,999,1584,1610]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="214.[115,146,1963,1983]" captionTargetBox="[88,1479,98,1935]" captionTargetPageId="214" captionText="Fig. 49. Distribution maps of species of Noronhia Stadtm.ex Thouars. N. pervilleana (KnobL.) H. Perrier to N. seyrigii H. Perrier." pageId="220" pageNumber="220">Fig. 49</figureCitation>
). It has been collected in flowers in March.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="220.[454,1475,1658,1797]" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hong-Wa" authorityYear="2016" box="[454,710,1658,1684]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" genus="Noronhia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="220" pageNumber="220" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="randrianaivoi">
<emphasis box="[454,710,1658,1684]" italics="true" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">Noronhia randrianaivoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently known only from a single collection made outside a protected area, where decline in habitat quality resulting from forest exploitation continues. With an AOO of just 
<quantity box="[763,825,1734,1760]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="220" pageNumber="220" unit="km" value="4.0">4 km</quantity>
<superScript attach="left" box="[825,834,1732,1746]" fontSize="6" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">2</superScript>
, a single location and projected continuing decline, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hong-Wa" authorityYear="2016" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" genus="Noronhia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="220" pageNumber="220" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="randrianaivoi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">N. randrianaivoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is assigned a preliminary status of “Critically Endangered” [CR B2(iii)].
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="220.[454,1474,1844,1984]" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hong-Wa" authorityYear="2016" box="[454,713,1844,1870]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" genus="Noronhia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="220" pageNumber="220" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="randrianaivoi">
<emphasis box="[454,713,1844,1870]" italics="true" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">Noronhia randrianaivoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName box="[879,1016,1844,1870]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Oleaceae" genus="Noronhia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="220" pageNumber="220" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ovalifolia">
<emphasis box="[879,1016,1844,1870]" italics="true" pageId="220" pageNumber="220">N. ovalifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by its nonwoody (vs. woody) petioles, thyrsoid inflorescences (vs. solitary flowers), and red (vs. pink) corolla. Distinguishing features of this species include short, non-woody petioles, ovate leaf blades, long, diffuse inflorescences, and cupuliform, red flowers.
</paragraph>
